'''Transcendental humanism''' in philosophy considers what is proper treatment of humans outside of nature and decides they have inherent rights, simply from being human.<ref>Ferry, Luc. 2002. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=_Z2tctBZg40C&lpg=PA139&dq=Transcendental%20Humanism&pg=PA135#v=onepage&q=Transcendental%20Humanism&f=false "Transcendental" Humanism]'' Man Made God: The Meaning of Life. University of Chicago Press. {{ISBN|0226244849}}</ref> It is also positive that man is capable of transcending the material self and can also free himself from surrounding influences. An example of this is when he thinks about himself and his character traits as if two different people.<ref>Vanheste, Jeroen. 2007. ''Guardians of the Humanist Legacy: The Classicism of T.S. Eliot's Criterion Network and Its Relevance to Our Postmodern World, Volume 26 of Philosophy of History and Culture'', pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=lITBxOMRJFQC&lpg=PA447&dq=Transcendental%20Humanism&pg=PA447#v=onepage&q=Transcendental%20Humanism&f=false 447] & [https://books.google.com/books?id=lITBxOMRJFQC&lpg=PA447&dq=Transcendental%20Humanism&pg=PA449#v=onepage&q=Transcendental%20Humanism&f=false 449] Brill. {{ISBN|9004161600}}</ref> Kant by the term meant humans are both a part of 'creation' and able to transcend reflexive obedience to the laws of nature.<ref>{{cite book|last=Allison|first=Henry E.|title=The Monist, Vol. 55, No. 2, Is Philosophy Human or Transcendental? |year=1971|publisher=Hegeler Institute|pages=182–207}}</ref>

